Introduction¶

Before exploring the data, I read the HERA data manual (Dara Storer) to understand the instrument and the collection process. The manual states that the data was collected by the HERA radio telescope. HERA stands for Hydrogen Epoch of Reoinization Array. Before I dive into the instrument and how the data was taken, I will provide background on what the instrument itself measures.

In astronomy, hydrogen plays an important role, specifically telling us about regions of space and what kind of star formation is happening there, if any. When a neutral hydrogen's electron changes its energy state (spin flip), an emission of energy 5.87433 μeV ($9.411708 * 10^-25$ J) leaves the atom. This phenomenon is called the hydrogen line, 21-centimeter line or H I line. This line often appears as a spectra in the radio spectrum (in the L band of the UHF band). Because of the range of the energy, it can easily pass through the Earth's atmosphere and be observed from the ground with little sky-sourced interference. Of course, current technology gets in the way (radios, cell towers, etc), but telescopes like HERA are built in remote places to try to avoid this as much as possible.

The 21cm line is used to determine the rotational curve of the galaxy, as hydrogen is everywhere in the universe, and the only difference in the 21cm lines they emit is the doppler shift that has affected it due to the stretching of space. Through this, galaxy mass can also be calculated. Because of how "easy" it is to observe from ground, this line is often used in Big Bang cosmology. It is used to learn about the universe at large redshifts (really long ago). Of particular interest are the recombination and reionization phases. Including redshift, this line is observed at frequencies from roughly 200 MHz to 9 MHz on Earth. One of the things that it is used for is mapping the intensity of reddshift, which allows analysis of how reionization happened in the universe (neutral hydrogen that was ionized doesn't emit 21 cm lines). More information can be found here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen_line.

Now that we have established why we care about hydrogen, let's talk about HERA. HERA is a radio telescope, which works similar to the way satellite TV dishes work, except much larger, and instead of just one dish, HERA is a 'network' of such dishes. This set-up is called an interferometer. HERA's dishes are arranged in a hexagonal pattern - see https://reionization.org/science/technical-design/. Interferometers allow for high resolution over a large area, and that is the advantage of using them. The base principle is that all the dishes (antennas) receive signals and send the to a central supercomputer, the correlator. The correlator takes the signals and compares them against all the other antennas. This results in either constructive or destructive interference. The resultant patterns are the end product with which I am working with. Now, for some terminology:

Baseline¶

A baseline refers to a pair of dishes. The length and orientation of a baseline is given by the separation vector between the two dishes.

Visibility¶

A visibility is the actual data product. Visibilities are a measure of the response of a particular baseline to incoming radiation from the sky, thus the final data product will contain a measurement of the visibility for each baseline in the array. Note: the visibilities are complex numbers, and this should be kept in mind.

There are two "types" of visibilities: cross-correlations and auto-correlations. Cross-correlations are visibilities corresponding to a baseline between two different antennas, which is the primary data product. Auto-correlations are visibilities corresponding to the correlation between an antenna and itself. Auto-correlations are not typically used for "science", but they can be useful in diagnosing problems with individual antennas, because they only contain information from one antenna.

More useful information¶

HERA collects data between 100MHz and 200MHz, and for four different polarizations (XX, YY, XY, YX). Therefore, the data products contain visibilities for each baseline, frequency, polarization, and time. The file dealt with in this analysis contains one polarization (XX) and a time axis of ten seconds. One particularly useful aspect of this data is that we expect sky signals to be quite steady in time (no rapid changes).

Goals¶

The following analysis aims to identify contaminants and remove them from the data, and to determine how much more sensitive the measurement is after the cuts, as compared to before. Since the provided data is rather large, I will analyze a part of the file that corresponds to a random sample of 100 out of the original 630 cross-correlation baselines. For increased clarity, I will be executing the analysis on one randomly chosen baseline (#25), and then iterating across the entire random sample. All code necessary for this analysis is presented in the Appendix at the very end, and should be run prior to the rest of the notebook.

Single antenna pair analysis¶

Signal removal¶

The data contains both sky signal (good) and contamination (bad). To make a background distribution, sky signal must be removed. The sky signal in this data is very steady in time in comparison to the measurements, as most of the sources are distant radio galaxies whose intensity is steady over millions of years, and they move slowly across the sky. The measurements are taken approximately every 10 seconds, so by subtracting neighboring time samples, the astrophysical signals can be removed. Many of the contaminants have a lot of variability, either because the brightness is quickly fluctuating or they are rapidly moving on the sky, thus this procedure will remove most of the sky signal, but much of the contamination will remain. Since I am using only one baseline, I do not have to worry about throwing out 𝑎=𝑏 measurements (e.g. 𝑣𝑎𝑎). I will mention this again when the entire sub-dataset is analyzed.

Discussion of Features and further visualization¶

Using the Radio Frequency Spectrum Allocation Chart for South Africa, found here,

it becomes obvious that some of the bright signals between 87.5 MHz and 108.0 MHz are due to radio station broadcasting. Radio stations transmit FM signals from 88.0 to 108 MHz. Therefore, to get a good analysis of the background, these frequencies will end up being removed. The peak around 137 MHz comes from an Orbcomm satellite, The "triangular" shape around 190 MHz is an analog television. While these are a rarity in the States, these are still in use in South Africa, where HERA is located. More insight on the sudden peaks in the data can be found in Mike Wilensky's memo: http://reionization.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/HERA082_TV_Info.pdf.

Jackknife tests¶

The natural progression in cleaning up this data is introducing a jackknife test. I will follow the steps to a jackknife test:

a) Come up with a concern.

One concern is that the background varies with frequency, considering there is broadcasting interfering with the data collection. Stated more concisely: Does the shape of the background distribution change depending on which frequency is observed?"

b) Identify a data cut such that if the concern is true the contamination should appear in one data set but not the other.

I will pick a frequency range of 65-80 MHz, and 155-170 MHz, since there are no obvious peaks in the data in those regions.

In [31]:
fig11()

c) Calculate the histograms for each dataset, including the error bars on the histogram. Plot the histograms.

In [32]:
n1, n2 = fig12()

So far, both the backgrounds in each time cut appear Gaussian in shape (parabolic in semi-log space). The last step is to perform the actual jackknife by subtracting the slices.

d) Subtract the histograms and check for consistency to within the expected error. Nota bene: the errors on the difference are not identical to the errors on each histogram individually.

In [33]:
fig13(n1, n2)

As can be seen from the above jackknife plot, the errors are centered around zero, which is good. However, the error bars do not all overlap the zero, meaning there is too much variance for the jackknife to pass. Of particular note is the negative difference in the initial bins, and the positive difference in the middle bins, which means that histogram one is much taller than two initially, and then histogram two overtakes it. This means that our concert is valid. Something not discussed previously, but is known to affect the data is Synchrotron radiation (see here: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Synchrotron_radiation#:~:text=Synchrotron%20radiation%20). This effect is dominantly present at lower frequency and results in the sky appearing much brighter at lower frequencies. Because Synchrotoron radiation is not thermally sourced, it is much brighter, and follows a power law. This means that this jackknife was not chosen well in that it does not account for this difference in brightness of the sky. If I chose frequency ranges closer to each other, this effect would not overwhelm the visibilities, and would possibly pass.

# shape is 20: ammount of times. Subtraction is of times (n+1) - (n), and there are 19 subtractions
def back_gone(line):
    clean1 = []
    for i in range(19):
        clean1.append(line[i+1]-line[i])
    clean1=np.array(clean1)
    return clean1

clean1 = back_gone(data_base)

# for all time
cleanest = []

for i in range(19):

    lowcut = abs(freqs-55).argmin()
    lowcut = np.arange(lowcut)
    radiocut = np.arange(abs(freqs-88).argmin(), abs(freqs-108).argmin())
    tvcut = np.arange(abs(freqs-190).argmin(), abs(freqs-193).argmin())
    totalcut = np.concatenate((lowcut, radiocut, tvcut))

    cleaner = np.abs(np.delete(clean1[i], totalcut))
    cleanfreq = np.delete(freqs, totalcut)

    for j in range(0,15):
        a = cleaner.argmax()
        b = cleaner.argmin()
        c = [a, b]
        cleanfreq = np.delete(cleanfreq, c)
        cleaner = np.abs(np.delete(cleaner, c))
        
    cleanest.append(cleaner)

def big_clean():
    np.random.seed(3)
    bline = []
    for i in range(len(pairs)):
        if pairs[i][0]!= pairs[i][1]:
            bline.append(pairs[i])
    blines = np.random.choice(np.arange(len(bline),dtype=int),size=100,replace=False)
    bs = np.array(bline)
    lines = bs[blines]
    
    avg1 = []
    for i in range(20):
        ma= []
        for j in range(len(lines)):
            sha = abs(uv.get_data(lines[j]))
            ma.append(sha[i])
        ma = np.array(ma)
        mc = ma.mean(axis=0)
        avg1.append(mc)
    avg1 = np.array(avg1)
    avg1.shape
    
    clean2 =[ ]
    for k in range(19):
        bt = []
        for m in range(len(lines)):
            d = abs(back_gone(uv.get_data(lines[m])))
            bt.append(d[k])
        bt = np.array(bt)
        mc = bt.mean(axis=0)
        clean2.append(mc)
    clean2 = np.array(clean2)
    clean2.shape
    return avg1, clean2
avg1, clean2 = big_clean()

    im = plt.imshow(np.log10(cleanest2),aspect='auto',interpolation='nearest')
    cbar = fig.colorbar(im,label='Visibility Intensity Log 10')
    axs.set_ylabel('Time', fontsize = 12)
    axs.set_xlabel('Frequency (MHz)', fontsize = 12)
    xticks = [int(i) for i in np.linspace(0,len(cleanfreq)-1,8)]
    _ = axs.set_xticks(xticks)
    xticklabels = np.around(cleanfreq[xticks],0)
    _ = axs.set_xticklabels(xticklabels)
    plt.title(f'Log10(Average Baseline), Signal removed', fontsize = 20)
    plt.show()
    return

def fig12():
    fig,ax=plt.subplots()
    low = abs(freqs-65).argmin()
    high = abs(freqs-80).argmin()
    cut = np.abs((cleanest2[:,low:high].flatten()))
    vro3 = cut
    plt.yscale('log')
    n1,bins,p=plt.hist(vro3,bins=75);
    b=bins[:-1]+(bins[1+20]-bins[0+20])/2
    plt.errorbar(b,n1,yerr=np.sqrt(n1),elinewidth=2,linewidth=0,color='k');
    plt.xlabel('Visibility Magnitudes', fontsize = 12)
    plt.ylabel('Counts', fontsize = 12);
    plt.title('Slice 1, Frequency cut 65 MHz - 80 MHz Histogram', fontsize = 20);

    fig,ax=plt.subplots()
    low = abs(freqs-155).argmin()
    high = abs(freqs-170).argmin()

    vro4 = cut
    plt.yscale('log')

def fig13(n2, n1):
    plt.subplots()
    diff=n2-n1
    plt.bar(np.arange(len(diff)),diff,width=1,yerr=np.sqrt(n1+n2))
    plt.xlabel('Bin #', fontsize = 14)
    plt.ylabel('Histogram Differences', fontsize = 14)
    plt.title('Jackknife test, Slice 2 - Slice 1', fontsize = 20);
    return
